# Project Rules: Node.js Express API

> RESTful API built with Express.js, TypeScript, and Prisma ORM.

## Project Identity

- **Type**: Backend API
- **Language**: TypeScript (Node.js 20+)
- **Framework**: Express.js 4.x
- **ORM**: Prisma
- **Testing**: Jest + Supertest
- **Validation**: Zod

---

## Coding Standards

### Naming Conventions

| Element | Convention | Example |
|---------|-----------|---------|
| Controllers | PascalCase | `UserController.ts` |
| Routes | kebab-case | `user-routes.ts` |
| Middleware | camelCase | `authMiddleware.ts` |
| Models | PascalCase (singular) | `User.ts` |
| Env vars | UPPER_SNAKE_CASE | `DATABASE_URL` |
| Directories | kebab-case | `user-management/` |

### File Organization

```
src/
├── controllers/    # Request handlers
├── routes/         # Express route definitions
├── middleware/      # Custom middleware
├── services/       # Business logic
├── repositories/   # Data access layer
├── types/          # TypeScript types/interfaces
├── utils/          # Utility functions
├── validators/     # Zod schemas
└── prisma/         # Prisma schema + migrations
```

---

## Critical Rules (🔴)

### Rule 1: ❌ Never put business logic in controllers

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — controller does too much
app.post('/users', async (req, res) => {
  const hashedPassword = await bcrypt.hash(req.body.password, 10);
  const user = await prisma.user.create({ data: { ...req.body, password: hashedPassword } });
  res.json(user);
});

// ✅ GOOD — controller delegates to service
app.post('/users', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await userService.createUser(req.body);
  res.status(201).json(user);
});
```

### Rule 2: ❌ Never use `req.body` without validation

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — no validation
const { email, password } = req.body;

// ✅ GOOD — Zod validation
const createUserSchema = z.object({
  email: z.string().email(),
  password: z.string().min(8),
});
const data = createUserSchema.parse(req.body);
```

### Rule 3: ✅ Always use async error handling middleware

```typescript
// ✅ Wrap async route handlers
const asyncHandler = (fn: RequestHandler) =>
  (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) =>
    Promise.resolve(fn(req, res, next)).catch(next);

app.get('/users', asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
  const users = await userService.getAll();
  res.json(users);
}));
```

---

## Important Guidelines (🟠)

- Use environment variables via `dotenv` — never hardcode secrets
- Structure error responses consistently: `{ error: string, code: string, details?: any }`
- Use HTTP status codes correctly (201 for create, 204 for delete, etc.)
- Implement request rate limiting for public endpoints

---

## Code Smells to Avoid

| ❌ Smell | ✅ Instead Do |
|----------|--------------|
| `app.use(cors())` without options | Configure specific origins |
| Raw SQL queries | Use Prisma Client |
| `console.log` for logging | Use structured logger (Winston/Pino) |
| Nested callbacks | Use async/await |
| God routes file | Split into modular route files |
